data.survey.strategy: I quite honestly was overwhelmed, but I tried to look for some patterns in the leads, although they seemed to run my mind around in circles and not tell me anything other than give me hunches.
I grouped everything together that was not contradictory or that could not be corroborated or substantiated without additional evidence.
I tried to tie things together and see if closed added up
I wanted to be right
i wanted to pick the right guy

I tried to keep up with the clues as they were added, but I had a hard time making any connections. I was trying to find corroborating evidence, matching the suspects with evidence connecting them to the scene and the crime, but everyone seemed equally suspect.
put together as many clues as possible that point to one person
checked for more clues that was relevant
Evaluating all the clues holistically
I tried to reason based on objective evidence and then branched out from there to see if the premises logically followed.
find clues that seemed related and consistent
With attention
Trying to adapt to the clues as they came in. It was just a matter of keeping things as organized as it could be.
i took a guess on what clues i thought were the right ones
I went with my gut
I thought to isolate a single set of description and key items. Anything that dealt with a different item or person I would not consider as essential evidence.
I went off of others promising leads
i thought for a while that i would stick to stuff that worked with "evidence" based clues... but then i noticed there were multiple evidence clues that suggested different things
Piecing together clues like a jigsaw puzzle

It was hard to determine if any of the clues weren't useful, and for a while I was moving them between lists almost at random trying to come up with a pattern or a set of clues that told a logical story as to how the crime was committed. This became harder as more clues were added, as they continued to all appear significant, so at the end it was more like I was adding clues to the significant list at random.
If the clues were too broad, then I considered it a dead end clue. If the clue could be useful in the future, I considered it a good clue.
clues
THE READING THE PASSAGE OF THE GIVEN ONE
I just tried to read all the cubes and decide what sounded relevant
Reading all clues and grouping like-kind ones together to form a pattern
I tried to look for things that were mentioned consistently and used critical reasoning to determine whether such things would be relevant
just trying to see what clues seemed to make sense together

I started from my own Promising Leads and added clues from collaborators that were related to my leads; eliminated those that mentioned completely unrelated data; and continued to add clues from collaborators that told a story.
No strategy - just went off of what made sense and what I read
I compared each clue to one another to see which ones stood out
I was excited to find that case.
Normal
Trying to figure out the narrative from the new pieces of information that filtered in.
I pieced as much information together, trying to get rid of any irrelevant information as soon as possible but didn't fully get the whole picture until the whole story was right in front of me.
I tried to find evidence that supported other evidence that I was seeing, and tried to disregard evidence that didn't seem to have as many supporting bits of evidence.
Try to sort the informations about each suspect.
clues
I read each clue and tried to decide if it was relevant or not to solving the case.
best conclusion
IMPROVE MY STRATEGY
